\begin_layout Standard
To evaluate the effects of the closures, we used a simple epidemiological-like
 model, in which the infections in the children cohorts depend on the overall
 state of epidemic plus the effect of schools.
 The former is linearly dependent on the product of the current magnitude
 of the epidemic and the current reproduction number, the latter linearly
 depends on the the product the current school restrictions, number of infected
 in the cohort in question, and the current reproduction number up to current
 contact restriction.
 We find the school closures as a whole as a significant inhibitor of the
 epidemic, with masks being provably efficient in the second degree and
 in secondary schools.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within the Discussion, we also discuss possible alternative explanations
 of the data and we show, that the one considering the string effect of
 school closures is the only of the considered hypotheses giving significant
 results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Czech Republic, each September first, children who completed their
 sixth year are obliged to enter the first year of elementary school.
 When the parents wish, a child who is six as late as by the end of the
 year can enter the first class, some children, on the other hand, start
 their school later for various, mostly developmental, reasons.
 If we neglect these exceptions, we can conclude that the first year students
 are six or seven; consequently the first degree (first five years) students
 belong to the age cohort 
\begin_inset Formula $6-11$
\end_inset

, the second degree (the sixth to the ninth year) students to the cohort
 
\begin_inset Formula $11-15$
\end_inset

 and the students of a secondary school, which typically takes four year
 in the Czech Republic, to the cohort 
\begin_inset Formula $15-19$
\end_inset

.
 The lowest age for admission to a kindergarten is three, so the the vast
 majority of children attending kindergartens falls into the cohort 
\begin_inset Formula $3-6$
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity we assume that, of the frontier one-year cohorts, half of
 the children belong to each competing school category, and that infections
 happening in a frontier cohort split by two between each category.
 Thus, number of cases by pre-school children over week 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 will then be 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}^{1}=Z_{t}^{3}+Z_{t}^{4}+Z_{t}^{5}+\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{6}$
\end_inset

, the number by the first degree 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}^{2}=\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{6}+Z_{t}^{7}+\dots+\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{11}$
\end_inset

, by the second degree 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}^{3}=\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{11}+Z_{t}^{12}+\dots+\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{15}$
\end_inset

 and by the secondary schools 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}^{4}=\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{15}+Z_{t}^{16}+\dots+\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{19},$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{t}^{j}$
\end_inset

 is the number of cases by 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-year old individuals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to these four cohorts, we studied the infections in the first
 two grades, which had been exclusively open during winter, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}^{2*}=\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{6}+Z_{t}^{7}+\frac{1}{2}Z_{t}^{8}$
\end_inset

 as number of cases therein.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In line with the mainstream epidemiological modeling we assume that the
 number of overall infections 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the previous number of infected and the overall contact
 reduction, where we take the last week incidence as a proxy for the former:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{t}\doteq r_{t}C_{t-1}X_{t-1};
\]

\end_inset

here, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 is the overall risk contact reduction within the overall population, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the current growth rate given that no contact reduction takes place
 (including the effects of virus mutations, possible seasonal influences,
 natural immunization and vaccination).
 For the school children we assume that additional infections come from
 schools.
 In particular, for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th school category, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{t}^{i}\doteq\alpha^{i}r_{t}C_{t}X_{t-1}+\gamma^{i}r_{t}S_{t-1}^{i}X_{t-1}^{i},\qquad S_{t-1}^{i}=D_{t-1}^{i}(1-\mu^{i}M_{t-1}^{i}),\label{eq:x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{i}$
\end_inset

 are constants, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\tau}^{i}$
\end_inset

 is the contact restriction at the school, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\tau}^{i}$
\end_inset

 is the indicator of wearing masks in classrooms and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{i}$
\end_inset

 is the (unknown) efficiency of masks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, assuming that, only a ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 of cases is reported, we may divide (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) by 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{t}\doteq r_{t}C_{t-1}Y_{t-1},\qquad Y_{t}^{i}\doteq\alpha^{i}r_{t}C_{t-1}Y_{t-1}+\gamma^{i}r_{t}S_{t-1}^{i}Y_{t-1}^{i},\qquad1\leq i\leq4,\label{eq:y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}\doteq cX_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the overall reported number of infections and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{i}\doteq cX_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 is reported infections number in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th cohort.
 By dividing by the size of the cohort 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{t}^{i}\doteq\beta^{i}r_{t}C_{t-1}P_{t-1}+\gamma^{i}r_{t}S_{t-1}^{i}P_{t-1}^{i},\qquad P_{t}^{i}=\frac{Y_{t}^{i}}{s^{i}},\qquad P_{t}=\frac{Y_{t}}{s},\qquad\beta^{i}=\frac{s}{s^{i}},\label{eq:prp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the size of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th cohort and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the whole population size.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:y"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) may serve for understanding of infection spread in schools and consequently
 for policy recommendations.
 Say that our goal is to keep new cases in the cohort less than some 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

 (for instance, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $50$
\end_inset

 cases per 100 thousand) and, when the numbers are higher, to decrease it
 by a ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 From (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:y"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we get that, for it to happen at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, it has to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{i}r_{t}C_{t-1}Y_{t-1}+\gamma^{i}r_{t}S_{t-1}^{i}Y_{t-1}^{i}\leq\max(\rho_{0}Y_{t-1}^{i},y_{0})
\]

\end_inset

which happens if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{t}:=\rho_{t}^{\alpha}+\rho_{t}^{\gamma}<\rho_{0},\qquad\rho_{t}^{\alpha}=\alpha^{i}r_{t}C_{t-1}\frac{Y_{t-1}}{\max(Y_{t-1}^{i},y_{0})},\qquad\rho_{t}^{\gamma}=\gamma^{i}r_{t}S_{t-1}^{i}\min\left(1,\frac{Y_{t-1}^{i}}{y_{0}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The equivalent formulation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), on the other hand, allows comparisons between cohorts, as it sepak in
 the language of infection probabilities: here the first/second summand
 evaluates probability of infection outside/inside the school.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the purpose of estimation, we may impose for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t-1}^{i}$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to get a linear model 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
P_{t}^{i}\doteq\beta^{i}Q_{t}+\gamma^{i}U_{t}+\delta^{i}V_{t}+\epsilon_{t},\\
Q_{t}=R_{t}P_{t},\qquad U_{t}=r_{t}D_{t-1}^{i}P_{t-1}^{i},\qquad V_{t}=r_{t}D_{t-1}M_{t-1}P_{t-1},\qquad\delta^{i}=-\mu\gamma^{i}.\label{eq:awls}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is centered error term for which we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}(\epsilon_{t})\sim Q_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

â€“ see Appendix for further details and more rigorous treatment.
 
\end_layout

