\begin_layout Standard
Our goal is to examine whether opening of schools contributes to the epidemic
 and whether masks play role in schools.
 To this end we assume that the expected weekly number number of newly infected
 children of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th cohort outside schools is Compound Poisson with mean 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{t}^{i}X_{t-1},\qquad X_{t-1}=\sum_{j=1}^{5}X_{t-1}^{j},\qquad\beta_{t}=R_{t}\beta,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is an unknown constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}$
\end_inset

 the reproduction number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, we hypothesize that the number of children of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th cohort, infected at school, is Compound Poisson with mean 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{t}^{i}(1-M_{t-1}^{i}\mu)S_{t-1}^{i}X_{t-1}^{i}\qquad\gamma_{t}^{i}=r_{t}\gamma^{i}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{i}$
\end_inset

 is an unknown efficiency of masks, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{i}$
\end_inset

 is an unknown constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}=R_{t}/C_{t-2}$
\end_inset

 is the the basic reproduction number, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The logic behind our model is following: without schools, the cohort of
 interest is infected 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

as usual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which means that the rate of their infection is proportional to the reproductio
n number and the number of infected in the whole population (a proxy for
 which up to constant is the daily number of infected).
 In schools, the situation is similar with the difference that we explicitly
 model the contact intensity therein (by variables 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and constants 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

), so the reproduction number has to be stripped of the influence of the
 overall contact restriction; therefore, we assume the infection to be proportio
nal to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 rather than to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summed up, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
X_{t}^{i}=\beta_{t}^{i}X_{t-1}+\gamma_{t}^{i}(1-M_{t-1}^{i}\mu^{i})S_{t-1}^{i}X_{t-1}^{i}+\epsilon_{t}^{i}\\
=\beta^{i}R_{t}X_{t-1}+\gamma^{i}r_{t}S_{t-1}^{i}X_{t-1}^{i}+\delta^{i}r_{t}M_{t-1}^{i}S_{t-1}^{i}X_{t-1}^{i}+\epsilon_{t}^{i},\qquad\delta^{i}=\gamma^{i}\mu^{i}.
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\epsilon_{t}^{i}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}(\epsilon_{t}^{i})$
\end_inset

 is, up to a constant, equal to the r.h.s.
 minus the residuum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we assume that the observed numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{1},\dots,Y_{t}^{5}$
\end_inset

 of the infected are proportional to the actual ones, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{i}=cX_{t}^{i}+e_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is an unknown constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}^{t}$
\end_inset

 are centered with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var(e_{t}^{i})\sim}X_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
Y_{t}^{i}=\beta^{i}I_{t}+\gamma^{i}U_{t}^{i}+\delta^{i}V_{t}^{i}+\eta_{t}^{i},\qquad I_{t}=R_{t}Y_{t-1},\qquad U_{t}^{i}=r_{t}S_{t-1}^{i}Y_{t-1}^{i},\qquad V_{t}^{i}=r_{t}M_{t-1}^{i}S_{t-1}^{i}Y_{t-1}^{i}\\
\eta_{t}^{i}=\frac{\epsilon_{t}^{i}}{c}+r_{t}\left[\beta^{i}\sum_{j=1}^{k}e_{t}^{j}+(\gamma^{i}S_{t-1}^{i}+\delta^{i}M_{t-1}^{i}S_{t-1}^{i})e_{t}^{i}\right]
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{\ensuremath{E}}\eta_{t}^{i}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var(}\eta_{i}^{i})=\sum_{j}d_{t}^{i,j}X_{t}^{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i,t}^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 As, in practice, the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 does not vary much in time, we approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{var}(\eta_{i}^{i})\doteq dX_{t}\doteq\frac{d}{c}I_{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is unknown parameter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our hypotheses are 
\end_layout

